              <span id="reviewTextContainer2905228649" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12541979937733764203"><i>The Perfect Wife</i> was a wild ride! My first J.P. Delaney book and likely not my last. <br/><br/>Abbie wakes up unsure of where she is or who she is with. She tries to readjust to her life as a wife to tech scion Tim Scott and mother to their autistic son, Danny. Abbie is told she was an artist but other information about her past is hazy. She attempts to retrieve her memories and fill in the mysterious gaps of the last five years. <br/><br/><i>The Perfect Wife</i> was disturbing and compelling. It raises interesting questi</span>
  <span id="freeText12541979937733764203" style="display:none"><i>The Perfect Wife</i> was a wild ride! My first J.P. Delaney book and likely not my last. <br /><br />Abbie wakes up unsure of where she is or who she is with. She tries to readjust to her life as a wife to tech scion Tim Scott and mother to their autistic son, Danny. Abbie is told she was an artist but other information about her past is hazy. She attempts to retrieve her memories and fill in the mysterious gaps of the last five years. <br /><br /><i>The Perfect Wife</i> was disturbing and compelling. It raises interesting questions like, how much technology is too much? I stayed guessing and engaged throughout the book and appreciated this original, different story.</span>
